well this weekend was great. my sister started learning how to snowboard. i had a great time meeting a lot of new kids. and the runs were pretty awesome up at smugglers notch. i went down this closed trail at the end of the day saturday. it was amazing, the best run i have ever been on. a foot and a half of untouched powder. wide flowing turns, snow flying 10 feet in the air with each one. spectacular. but here's the catch. a ski patrol guy saw me go down, and cut me off at the bottom. he clipped my ticket for the day. but told me that i could go to the ski patrol place and see if i would get it back. so after he said that i was happy again. the rest of the run was just as amazing, so it was totally worth it. and i got a lift ticket for the next day anyways.

as much as a enjoyed the weekend half of me didnt want to be there. this whole thing sucks...
it wasn't supposed to be anything but i wanted it to be more. i miss court, miss her smile, just being with eachother, i knew i would. but she lives 4 hours away most the year...
even if this isn't one sided like i think it is, i wouldnt want to put her through trying to make something work when we never got to see eachother.  i don't know, just what's been on my mind. friends with benefits never works, if that's even what it was, i don't know, i didnt want to say anything for the fear of her not wanting to spend time with me before she left.
im just rambling

this entry is for cal because he has nothing better to do at work than read this stuff. the last week has been mind blowing. this is the entire story from beginning to end:
     As many of you may know, I took a trip to Honduras in August with my church. We went to La Entrada to build latrines, beds, and tables for many of the local families along with spending time in a school with all the kids from the area. When we were at one of the sites that was getting a latrine, I saw one of the most shocking things I have seen in my life. After all the poverty I had seen, people with 1 set of clothes, no water, starving to death in 1 room adobe huts with 6 kids sleeping on the floor; I didn't think i could see anything else that would suprise me. We were standing outside this house planning how we would install the latrine and someone pointed out that there were small person-like molding out of dog feces. These kids had no toys, they were poor to the point that they found entertainment in playing with their dog's refuse. 
     So the story continues, I was talking to my mom when I came home. She didn't understand how poor these kid's truly were. And I told her this story. She has now made herself a goal, she asked me tonight how many kids I thought were in this entire town. I told her 20,000 as an uneducated guess. She plans to send 20,000 toys down to these kids, these starving kids with nothing. A week ago she spoke with Ken Ballinger about sending down toys, he said there would be room in the next shipment my church sends down for 200 or so. He didn't think she would be able to get that many in a few weeks time. After a week, she has been coming home with bags upon bags full. We have somewhere between 500 and 1000 at the moment. The goal isn't realistic, but anythign is possible. She is going to do this or die trying. I can't begin to explain the overwhelming respect I have for my mother. I am so impressed, so amazed that she is struggling between keeping our household together and running a business and she finds the time to do something like this. She is coming next year, my sister and father don't know, and probably won't until a few weeks before we go, but she is coming. She is going to see the faces that she has worked so hard to bring a smile to. I can't wait, this is going to be an amazing trip. If anyone has extra toys, stuffed animals, frisbees, balls, dolls, anythign that would be appropriate for kids to play with in a CHRISTIAN culture (aka no army men or guns) please let me know, or bring them to my house or give them to me in any way you see fit. Everything helps.

jason

hey everyone, i got back from Honduras about this time last night. it was an amazing trip, i think everyone needs to see the things i saw, it really puts your life in perspective. makes you realize how lucky you are and how worthless our worries and concerns are when millions of people around the world are worried about getting food for their kids and worried about their house falling apart in a storm. think about it, this trip helped affirm my calling to ministry, i have the overwhelming feeling that i have been put here to serve. that i need to leave my material desires behind and help people. i know what i want to do and nothing is going to stop me. ill post pictures when i get them developed.

the people i met had nothing, they lived in 1 room tin huts. sometimes sleeping on the floor with as many as 11 kids. and they were so concerned with putting others first. these people would share everything they had. they went out of their way to help us. i can't explain it in words, this was a life changing experience and i made friends that i will keep in touch with for a long time. 

i saw God in the most unlikely people on this trip. will's father, Butch, had kids on his lap, he hugged them and held them and loved them like they were his own. 

i left to help the people of La Entrada and they did more for me than i could do for them with a million dollars. they helped me find my calling, find what i want to do the rest of my life. and i thank them for that.

i dropped off my luggage at church then will and i met dan, lauryn, meredith and another girl who's name leaves me. ended up walking around west chester and i saw whitney of all people. she was tripping on shrooms lol, typical. we drove them all out to the mall and went to the fair .
